acqinfo.p: The Committee of 100 on the Federal City donated these records in 1986. Dorn McGrath, former chair of the Committee gave a gift in 1989. A final donation was made by former chair David Grinnel in 1991.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The mission of the Committee of 100 on the Federal City is to safeguard and advance the fundamental planning, environmental and aesthetic values inherited from the L'Enfant Plan and the McMillan Commission that give Washington its historic distinction, natural beauty and overall livability. The Committee advances the proposition that planning of the highest caliber is essential to ensure for residents of Washington D.C. - indeed for all the citizens of the United States for whom the Nation's Capital is a symbol - the attainment and preservation of a city worthy of the Nation. From specific proposals such as its plan for the redesign of the Whitehurst Freeway below Georgetown, to more general initiatives, such as testimony on regional air quality standards and support for reinvigorating of the NCPC, the Committee continues its broad campaign for exemplary planning in the Nation's Capital. The Committee is engaging in close consultation on planning issues with the Congress and the District of Columbia Government. The Committee has also established its own ad hoc subcommittee on regional planning to work in liaison with kindred organizations in Maryland and Virginia.

The Committee of 100 on the federal City was organized in 1923 by the American Planning and Civic Association (APCA) in order to study the problems facing the Nation's capital. Frederic A. Delano, Uncle to President Franklin Delano Roosevelt, was the first Chairman of the Committee. Following its conception, the Committee of 100 has served as a citizens forum discussing planning issues that confront the District. The Committee separated itself from the APCA in 1965 and incorporated as a non-profit organization.

For over half a century, the Committee has attracted to its membership architects, planners, landscape architects, lawyers, conservationists, historians, and concerned citizens from diverse professions and backgrounds. It has sought to rally national, regional, and local organizations which share in the mission of safeguarding the heritage of Washington, D.C. Not only is the Committee of 100 on the Federal City the oldest planning body and the oldest citizens' forum on planning issues in the Nation's Capital, it is also one of the most effective and vigorous organizations of its kind.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection contains correspondence, reports, minutes, publications, newspaper articles, memorandum, bank statements, maps, and blueprints. The material dates from 1932-91 with the bulk of the material falling within the dates 1950-1987.

The majority of the documents focus on city planning and transportation issues. These detail the various highway and rapid transit projects facing the district, as well as looking at zoning regulations and legal procedures and the debates and discussions between different committee members on many topics concerning planning issues in the District of Columbia. Another portion of the collection deals with the founding and governing procedures of the committee including early historical documents. An early history of the committee was donated by Eric T. Menke. Significant people included in these records are Peter S. Craig, Frederic Delano, Harlean James, Ulysses Grant III, Dorn Mc Grath, John Nolen Jr., Constance Green, and Polly Shackleton. Some of the issues covered are the Three Sisters Bridge Controversy; WMATA projects, such as the Metro Rail design and planning; the Pennsylvania Avenue Development Corporation; Cleveland Park Historical Society; Potomac River Conversation; Inner Loop Freeway Planning (I-65 and I-295), Federal Triangle, Old Post Office; parking issues; and building height restrictions.

The collection as a whole provides researchers with information on the founding and organization of the Committee of 100, while showing how it functioned as citizens forum for discussing the great planning issues facing the Nation's Capital.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into eight series: Organizational history and background, Chronological files, General correspondence, Committee records, Financial records, Subject/Issues files, Oversize records, and Accession 2011.068

scopecontent.p: This series contains articles of incorporation, statements, and reports. These materials cover 1965-81. This series details the structure, activities, and purpose for the Committee of 100. It also provides a brief history of its founding and initial organization.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains pamphlets, correspondence, newspaper articles, and reports. This material dates from 1939-71. The material in this collection was gathered by Eric T. Menke, a long time committee member, in order to detail the history of the Committee of 100.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence that dates from 1959-81. Most of the correspondence relates to committee business such as office procedures and personal contact between committee members, and includes invitations and personal responses.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The series contains minutes, correspondence, dues cards, and mailing lists. These materials date from 1944-87. The types of records in this series include membership and Trustees. The files with meeting minutes also contain supplemental materials handed out at the meeting. This series also has lists of the general members and Trustees of the Committee.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The files are not in alphabetical or chronological order. The folders are in the order that they were in during accession.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, checkbooks, bills, receipts, tax forms, and Treasurer's reports. This material dates from 1966-82. The correspondence contains information on legal funds and various project specific fundings. Special highlights include PIPA account details and information concerning Three Sisters Bridge, the Volpe Trial, and other highway projects. Many of the receipts and bills in this series deal with general office tasks such as duplicating and printing services.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is not organized in chronological or alphabetical order. The folders are in the order that they were in when the collection was first accessioned.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, reports, publications, pamphlets, memorandum, Congressional bills, newspaper articles, maps and blueprints. This material dates form 1954-91. The broad subjects within the collection include city planning, ecology/conservation, historic preservation, and transportation both general, and highways. These materials represent the real involvement of the Committee with the various planning aspects of the Nation's Capital. They contain information on citizens groups, court cases, and planning commissions which shows how the Committee of 100 used its influence to solve many of the problems facing the District of Columbia.

The material related to transportation contains information on the Three Sisters Bridge controversy, the Volpe Trial, and Interstate construction in the D.C. Metropolitan Area. For the topic of city planning there is extensive documentation on the Pennsylvania Avenue Development Corporation and the National Capital Planning Commission and blueprints of projects such as the Old Post Office and Federal Triangle.

arrangement.p: This series is not organized in chronological or alphabetical order. The folders are in the order that they were in when the collection was first accessioned.
